WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.420 --> 00:00:03.400
ALANA WEISS: Good morning.

00:00:03.400 --> 00:00:05.880
My name is Alana Weiss, and
today it is my pleasure to

00:00:05.880 --> 00:00:09.210
welcome Adam Grant to the
Leading at Google series.

00:00:09.210 --> 00:00:12.040
Adam Grant is the youngest
tenured professor and single

00:00:12.040 --> 00:00:14.720
highest rated teacher at
the Wharton School.

00:00:14.720 --> 00:00:18.360
He is a former record setting
advertising director, junior

00:00:18.360 --> 00:00:22.850
Olympic springboard diver, and
professional magician.

00:00:22.850 --> 00:00:26.970
He has been honored as one of
"Business Week's" favorite

00:00:26.970 --> 00:00:29.950
professors and one of the
world's top 40 business

00:00:29.950 --> 00:00:32.500
professors under 40.

00:00:32.500 --> 00:00:35.230
Adam is a regular contributor
to Google's People &amp;

00:00:35.230 --> 00:00:38.860
Innovation lab, and he also
has consulted with clients

00:00:38.860 --> 00:00:41.570
ranging from the NFL
to Goldman Sachs

00:00:41.570 --> 00:00:43.540
to the United Nations.

00:00:43.540 --> 00:00:46.690
He holds a Ph.D in
organizational psychology from

00:00:46.690 --> 00:00:51.120
the University of Michigan and
a BA from Harvard University.

00:00:51.120 --> 00:00:54.510
Today, Adam will share from his
new book "Give and Take."

00:00:54.510 --> 00:00:57.146
Please join me in welcoming
Adam Grant.

00:00:57.146 --> 00:01:02.390
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:02.390 --> 00:01:03.170
ADAM GRANT: Good morning.

00:01:03.170 --> 00:01:04.400
Thank you guys so much
for having me.

00:01:04.400 --> 00:01:05.830
I'm truly delighted
to be here.

00:01:05.830 --> 00:01:08.540
It's always an honor and a treat
to speak to Googlers,

00:01:08.540 --> 00:01:09.780
and also to see lots
of friendly

00:01:09.780 --> 00:01:10.870
faces in the audience.

00:01:10.870 --> 00:01:13.080
And I'm going to try to turn all
of those friendly faces in

00:01:13.080 --> 00:01:16.650
a more negative direction
in the next few minutes.

00:01:16.650 --> 00:01:19.950
The place I want to start is I
want to talk for maybe 35 or

00:01:19.950 --> 00:01:20.970
40 minutes or so.

00:01:20.970 --> 00:01:22.800
We'll have lots of interactive
discussion throughout, and

00:01:22.800 --> 00:01:24.870
then hopefully open it up then
for some questions and more

00:01:24.870 --> 00:01:25.370
discussion.

00:01:25.370 --> 00:01:27.880
But the place to begin, really,
is to say that I'm

00:01:27.880 --> 00:01:30.520
interested in success and what
makes some people and

00:01:30.520 --> 00:01:33.020
organizations incredibly
productive and effective and

00:01:33.020 --> 00:01:35.410
why other people, perhaps,
are less so.

00:01:35.410 --> 00:01:37.430
And at the end of the day, what
I want to know is how can

00:01:37.430 --> 00:01:40.772
every person in this room own
a face that looks like this?

00:01:40.772 --> 00:01:42.250
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:01:42.250 --> 00:01:44.030
ADAM GRANT: And I know some of
you are thinking right now,

00:01:44.030 --> 00:01:46.160
well, I already own that face.

00:01:46.160 --> 00:01:48.490
And the question is, well, how
could you own it more often?

00:01:48.490 --> 00:01:51.430
Or how could you spread it to
the other people around you?

00:01:51.430 --> 00:01:54.150
And as an organizational
psychologist, when I started

00:01:54.150 --> 00:01:56.520
doing research in this area
about 10 years ago, I found

00:01:56.520 --> 00:01:59.370
that there were three ways
to get to this face--

00:01:59.370 --> 00:02:01.480
hard work, talent, and luck.

00:02:01.480 --> 00:02:04.180
If you want to be effective in
any domain or any profession

00:02:04.180 --> 00:02:06.790
or any field, you have to
develop a strong work ethic,

00:02:06.790 --> 00:02:11.650
you have to really be mastery or
expertise oriented so that

00:02:11.650 --> 00:02:14.680
you develop true skills, and, as
Malcolm Gladwell told us in

00:02:14.680 --> 00:02:17.270
"Outliers," you have to find
yourself in the right place at

00:02:17.270 --> 00:02:18.340
the right time.

00:02:18.340 --> 00:02:19.560
And I think that's all true.

00:02:19.560 --> 00:02:21.570
But for me, it was missing a
really important part of

00:02:21.570 --> 00:02:24.350
success in this connected world
that we all live in--

00:02:24.350 --> 00:02:26.240
our interactions with others.

00:02:26.240 --> 00:02:27.490
Most of you work in teams.

00:02:27.490 --> 00:02:28.970
Many of you have clients.

00:02:28.970 --> 00:02:32.520
Some of you have more managers
than you would like, perhaps.

00:02:32.520 --> 00:02:34.410
And the question is, how does
the way that you interact with

00:02:34.410 --> 00:02:37.310
those people every day, shape
the results that you achieve,

00:02:37.310 --> 00:02:39.010
the promotions that you gain?

00:02:39.010 --> 00:02:41.750
And ultimately, perhaps also the
meaning in the happiness

00:02:41.750 --> 00:02:43.330
that you obtain.

00:02:43.330 --> 00:02:45.370
So when I was trying to get to
the bottom of this, I came

00:02:45.370 --> 00:02:46.840
across a really inspiring
quote.

00:02:46.840 --> 00:02:48.070
It was from Robert Benchley.

00:02:48.070 --> 00:02:50.000
And Benchley said there are only
two kinds of people in

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:51.170
the world--

00:02:51.170 --> 00:02:53.450
those who divide the world into
two kinds of people, and

00:02:53.450 --> 00:02:55.520
those who don't.

00:02:55.520 --> 00:02:57.860
And I thought that was a
really profound way of

00:02:57.860 --> 00:03:00.700
criticizing those of us in the
psychology world who like to

00:03:00.700 --> 00:03:03.390
oversimplify all of the richness
and complexity of

00:03:03.390 --> 00:03:04.480
human beings.

00:03:04.480 --> 00:03:06.770
And I told myself that if I
ever wrote a book I would

00:03:06.770 --> 00:03:10.810
never dumb down all of the
complexity of people into just

00:03:10.810 --> 00:03:12.200
two categories.

00:03:12.200 --> 00:03:14.850
Which is why today I am proud to
announce to you that if you

00:03:14.850 --> 00:03:16.990
want to capture everything
important about interpersonal

00:03:16.990 --> 00:03:19.260
interaction in organizations
you need not two, but three

00:03:19.260 --> 00:03:21.240
categories.

00:03:21.240 --> 00:03:23.290
No, actually, in all
seriousness, there's a good

00:03:23.290 --> 00:03:26.080
amount of evidence across
industries and across cultures

00:03:26.080 --> 00:03:27.580
that there are three fundamental
motives that

00:03:27.580 --> 00:03:29.230
people bring to their
interactions.

00:03:29.230 --> 00:03:31.890
I call them reciprocity styles,
basically trying to

00:03:31.890 --> 00:03:34.490
capture the way that you
approach your interactions

00:03:34.490 --> 00:03:36.860
with other people into
exchanging value.

00:03:36.860 --> 00:03:40.100
On one end of the reciprocity
spectrum we have the takers.

00:03:40.100 --> 00:03:43.350
The people that we all love to
hate who try to get as much as

00:03:43.350 --> 00:03:46.510
possible from others and try to
shirk having to contribute

00:03:46.510 --> 00:03:50.010
back and often specialize in
things like relentless self

00:03:50.010 --> 00:03:53.630
promotion, hogging credit, and
maybe stepping on a few people

00:03:53.630 --> 00:03:55.650
on their way to the top.

00:03:55.650 --> 00:03:57.890
Now, on the other end of the
spectrum we have these very,

00:03:57.890 --> 00:04:01.260
very strange characters
that I call givers.

00:04:01.260 --> 00:04:06.070
And for some odd reason, they
actually enjoy helping others.

00:04:06.070 --> 00:04:08.360
Not necessarily philanthropists
or volunteers,

00:04:08.360 --> 00:04:10.300
but rather the kinds of people
who do a lot of knowledge

00:04:10.300 --> 00:04:12.910
sharing, who are always
introducing people and making

00:04:12.910 --> 00:04:16.290
connections, who may step
up to provide mentoring.

00:04:16.290 --> 00:04:19.260
Now, very few of us
fall purely in the

00:04:19.260 --> 00:04:20.920
taker or giver category.

00:04:20.920 --> 00:04:23.010
Most people, it turns out, if
you look at the data, are what

00:04:23.010 --> 00:04:24.280
I call matchers.

00:04:24.280 --> 00:04:26.010
And a matcher is somebody who
has tried to keep an even

00:04:26.010 --> 00:04:27.640
balance of give and take.

00:04:27.640 --> 00:04:28.850
Quid pro quo.

00:04:28.850 --> 00:04:29.830
Tit for tat.

00:04:29.830 --> 00:04:33.720
If I do you a favor, I expect
you to do me one in return.

00:04:33.720 --> 00:04:36.720
And that seems like a safe and
reasonable way to live your

00:04:36.720 --> 00:04:38.000
professional life.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:40.300
But my question is, is it the
best way to live your

00:04:40.300 --> 00:04:41.540
professional life?

00:04:41.540 --> 00:04:44.590
Is being a matcher, which most
people choose to do, actually

00:04:44.590 --> 00:04:46.480
the best path to success?

00:04:46.480 --> 00:04:48.380
I'm going to try to shed some
light on that today.

00:04:48.380 --> 00:04:50.940
But before we do that, let's
dive into the takers a little

00:04:50.940 --> 00:04:54.300
bit and say, how would you
recognize a taker even if you

00:04:54.300 --> 00:04:55.750
didn't know that person?

00:04:55.750 --> 00:04:57.680
So I prepared a little test,
first of all, for you to

00:04:57.680 --> 00:05:00.290
figure out if you yourself
are a taker.

00:05:00.290 --> 00:05:02.400
If you could take a moment and
take the test, I'll tell you

00:05:02.400 --> 00:05:05.114
whether you passed.

00:05:05.114 --> 00:05:13.790
AUDIENCE: [CHUCKLING]

00:05:13.790 --> 00:05:16.410
ADAM GRANT: Now, I hope this is
the only thing I will say

00:05:16.410 --> 00:05:19.010
today that is not based
on data or evidence.

00:05:19.010 --> 00:05:21.080
But I sincerely believe that
the longer it takes you to

00:05:21.080 --> 00:05:23.680
laugh, the worse your score
is on the taker spectrum.

00:05:23.680 --> 00:05:26.320
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:05:26.320 --> 00:05:27.840
ADAM GRANT: Obviously, there are
a couple different paths

00:05:27.840 --> 00:05:28.850
to becoming a taker.

00:05:28.850 --> 00:05:33.220
One is to be a narcissistic,
to be insecure, to believe

00:05:33.220 --> 00:05:36.450
that you have to be superior to
others to be successful and

00:05:36.450 --> 00:05:39.610
carry around this assumption
that the world is zero sum.

00:05:39.610 --> 00:05:41.650
A second path to becoming a
taker, which I want to talk a

00:05:41.650 --> 00:05:44.200
little bit about today, is
having been taken advantage of

00:05:44.200 --> 00:05:47.340
one too many times as a matcher
or a giver, and

00:05:47.340 --> 00:05:49.370
believing if I don't put
myself first in this

00:05:49.370 --> 00:05:52.660
dog-eat-dog competitive
world, nobody will.

00:05:52.660 --> 00:05:54.620
There's a third path to becoming
a taker which I'm not

00:05:54.620 --> 00:05:56.000
going to talk about today,
it's called being a

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:56.700
psychopath.

00:05:56.700 --> 00:05:58.460
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:05:58.460 --> 00:05:59.840
ADAM GRANT: So all right.

00:05:59.840 --> 00:06:00.900
How do you spot a taker?

00:06:00.900 --> 00:06:01.980
How do you recognize one?

00:06:01.980 --> 00:06:04.310
There's an actual study by
Chatterjee and Hambrick

00:06:04.310 --> 00:06:07.420
showing that you can tell
whether a CEO is a taker just

00:06:07.420 --> 00:06:09.980
by looking at that person's
photograph in a company's

00:06:09.980 --> 00:06:12.030
annual report.

00:06:12.030 --> 00:06:14.010
Here are photos of two CEOs.

00:06:14.010 --> 00:06:16.950
I would argue that one is
a taker, one's a giver.

00:06:16.950 --> 00:06:20.070
These guys both built very
successful companies.

00:06:20.070 --> 00:06:22.450
Both, interestingly, in the
1970s worked in the Nixon

00:06:22.450 --> 00:06:25.000
administration, which I believe
is where one learned

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:25.940
some of his taking habits.

00:06:25.940 --> 00:06:27.510
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:06:27.510 --> 00:06:28.820
ADAM GRANT: And the
question is--

00:06:28.820 --> 00:06:31.260
these photos were taken right
from their annual reports--

00:06:31.260 --> 00:06:34.750
can you tell which of the two
of them is the taker just by

00:06:34.750 --> 00:06:36.950
looking at their faces
or their clothing?

00:06:36.950 --> 00:06:39.180
Take a second to study them, and
then I'm going to ask you

00:06:39.180 --> 00:06:42.140
to weigh in with your votes,
and then justify your bets.

00:06:45.830 --> 00:06:50.520
[WHISTLING "JEOPARDY!" THEME]

00:06:50.520 --> 00:06:53.810
So as of 2013, most Wharton
undergrads don't recognize

00:06:53.810 --> 00:06:54.470
that music.

00:06:54.470 --> 00:06:56.560
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:06:56.560 --> 00:06:59.485
ADAM GRANT: Which I find
to be a great tragedy.

00:06:59.485 --> 00:07:02.276
Like, is that "The Twilight
Zone?" No.

00:07:02.276 --> 00:07:04.600
All right, how many people
think the guy on your

00:07:04.600 --> 00:07:08.250
right is the taker?

00:07:08.250 --> 00:07:09.370
How many of you don't
know which one is

00:07:09.370 --> 00:07:09.980
the guy on your right?

00:07:09.980 --> 00:07:11.790
No, OK.

00:07:11.790 --> 00:07:13.440
Show your hands again, the
guy on your right.

00:07:13.440 --> 00:07:14.780
The taker.

00:07:14.780 --> 00:07:16.330
Show your hands high, we want
to know who you are.

00:07:16.330 --> 00:07:17.210
OK.

00:07:17.210 --> 00:07:18.780
Why?

00:07:18.780 --> 00:07:20.430
Why do you think
he's the taker?

00:07:20.430 --> 00:07:20.980
Yes.

00:07:20.980 --> 00:07:24.670
AUDIENCE: Well, his eyes
look less kind.

00:07:24.670 --> 00:07:25.400
ADAM GRANT: His eyes.

00:07:25.400 --> 00:07:26.640
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:07:26.640 --> 00:07:28.990
ADAM GRANT: So you can see
kindness in the eyes.

00:07:28.990 --> 00:07:29.872
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:07:29.872 --> 00:07:32.080
I'm going with what I have.

00:07:32.080 --> 00:07:33.590
ADAM GRANT: Who are you, and
where can I learn that skill?

00:07:33.590 --> 00:07:35.620
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:07:35.620 --> 00:07:37.680
ADAM GRANT: So I'm told that
that may be a built-in feature

00:07:37.680 --> 00:07:38.890
to the Google Glasses.

00:07:38.890 --> 00:07:42.210
But what about the eyes signals
kindness to you?

00:07:45.500 --> 00:07:46.440
AUDIENCE: I don't--

00:07:46.440 --> 00:07:49.270
I'm also completely basing
this off like my exp--

00:07:49.270 --> 00:07:49.950
ADAM GRANT: Rightfully so.

00:07:49.950 --> 00:07:50.880
What else could you use?

00:07:50.880 --> 00:07:51.900
I've given you no information.

00:07:51.900 --> 00:07:54.695
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:07:54.695 --> 00:07:58.332
AUDIENCE: So I feel like the
one on the left, they're a

00:07:58.332 --> 00:08:01.970
