You can't control these muscles
right next to your

00:10:00.190 --> 00:10:03.430
eyes, and so when you're
experiencing genuine positive

00:10:03.430 --> 00:10:06.810
emotions you will see those
crinkle or wrinkle next to

00:10:06.810 --> 00:10:07.560
your smile.

00:10:07.560 --> 00:10:09.830
But if it's a fake smile,
you won't see those.

00:10:09.830 --> 00:10:12.770
The problem is both takers and
givers and matchers, too, are

00:10:12.770 --> 00:10:15.080
capable of fake smiles.

00:10:15.080 --> 00:10:17.780
In fact, there are a lot of
takers, also, who engage in

00:10:17.780 --> 00:10:19.400
very genuine smiles.

00:10:19.400 --> 00:10:22.270
There's a term in psychology
called duping delight, which

00:10:22.270 --> 00:10:25.140
captures the sheer joy you
experience if you're a taker

00:10:25.140 --> 00:10:27.010
after lying to somebody and
getting away with it.

00:10:27.010 --> 00:10:28.670
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:10:28.670 --> 00:10:30.720
ADAM GRANT: So you can see this
very genuine smile from a

00:10:30.720 --> 00:10:32.660
taker who's like, I just took
you to the cleaners.

00:10:32.660 --> 00:10:34.085
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:10:34.085 --> 00:10:34.560
ADAM GRANT: All right.

00:10:34.560 --> 00:10:37.050
So those are a couple cues.

00:10:37.050 --> 00:10:39.730
I am sorry to report that the
man on the right I would say

00:10:39.730 --> 00:10:41.650
is the giver.

00:10:41.650 --> 00:10:43.350
So some of you will be
feeling bad about

00:10:43.350 --> 00:10:44.310
yourselves right now.

00:10:44.310 --> 00:10:46.070
Please don't.

00:10:46.070 --> 00:10:47.520
I will make the rest of
you feel bad about

00:10:47.520 --> 00:10:49.130
yourselves in a moment.

00:10:49.130 --> 00:10:51.150
The guy on the right, some of
you may have heard of him, his

00:10:51.150 --> 00:10:54.640
name is Jon Huntsman, Sr. He
built the building that I

00:10:54.640 --> 00:10:56.160
teach in at Wharton.

00:10:56.160 --> 00:10:58.330
He's one of 19 people on Earth
who have given away over $1

00:10:58.330 --> 00:10:59.650
billion dollars.

00:10:59.650 --> 00:11:01.470
Seemingly pretty generous.

00:11:01.470 --> 00:11:03.700
He also had a son recently
who may have been a

00:11:03.700 --> 00:11:05.570
presidential candidate.

00:11:05.570 --> 00:11:07.470
If you've read his book "Winners
Never Cheat," he has

00:11:07.470 --> 00:11:10.420
some incredible stories of going
out of his way to give

00:11:10.420 --> 00:11:13.550
to others, including after the
financial markets crashed, he

00:11:13.550 --> 00:11:15.850
couldn't fulfill all of his
charitable commitments so he

00:11:15.850 --> 00:11:18.540
took out a personal loan to
deliver on his promises to

00:11:18.540 --> 00:11:20.040
help various causes.

00:11:20.040 --> 00:11:22.580
There's also a couple stories,
actually, of him being in big

00:11:22.580 --> 00:11:25.850
merger and acquisition
negotiations and ending up

00:11:25.850 --> 00:11:28.490
feeling like the CEO at the
other side of the table is in

00:11:28.490 --> 00:11:30.430
a really bad situation,
had just lost

00:11:30.430 --> 00:11:31.720
his wife due to cancer--

00:11:31.720 --> 00:11:33.640
cancer, unfortunately,
has affected a lot of

00:11:33.640 --> 00:11:34.600
the Huntsman family--

00:11:34.600 --> 00:11:36.670
and Huntsman basically signed a
deal instead of claiming an

00:11:36.670 --> 00:11:40.680
extra $200 million because he
empathized with the other guy.

00:11:40.680 --> 00:11:43.210
So I think he's a pretty
powerful example of a giver.

00:11:43.210 --> 00:11:45.970
The man on the left I would
say was the taker.

00:11:45.970 --> 00:11:47.500
Did anybody recognize him?

00:11:47.500 --> 00:11:48.460
AUDIENCE: Ken Lay.

00:11:48.460 --> 00:11:49.210
ADAM GRANT: OK, those
of you who

00:11:49.210 --> 00:11:50.280
recognized him, that's cheating.

00:11:50.280 --> 00:11:52.320
You can't use actual information
about him.

00:11:52.320 --> 00:11:53.080
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:11:53.080 --> 00:11:55.005
ADAM GRANT: You're supposed to
use the photo and the clothes.

00:11:55.005 --> 00:11:56.340
But yeah, Ken Lay.

00:11:56.340 --> 00:11:58.604
What do you know
about Ken Lay?

00:11:58.604 --> 00:11:59.918
AUDIENCE: Enron.

00:11:59.918 --> 00:12:00.360
ADAM GRANT: Enron.

00:12:00.360 --> 00:12:02.530
Yeah, one of the primary
villains in that scandal.

00:12:02.530 --> 00:12:04.820
If you've seen or read "The
Smartest Guys in the Room,"

00:12:04.820 --> 00:12:07.660
you've been exposed to many,
many examples of him having

00:12:07.660 --> 00:12:09.430
been a taker.

00:12:09.430 --> 00:12:11.790
Now, the question is, how did
you know, if you didn't

00:12:11.790 --> 00:12:14.060
recognize him, that
he was a taker?

00:12:14.060 --> 00:12:16.530
And I'm sad to report that there
is nothing in either of

00:12:16.530 --> 00:12:17.880
these two photos that
says anything

00:12:17.880 --> 00:12:18.765
about givers and takers.

00:12:18.765 --> 00:12:19.720
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:12:19.720 --> 00:12:21.510
ADAM GRANT: I just like to see
what people are willing to

00:12:21.510 --> 00:12:22.645
read into meaningless
photographs.

00:12:22.645 --> 00:12:24.191
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:12:24.191 --> 00:12:26.310
ADAM GRANT: No, in all
seriousness, I show you these

00:12:26.310 --> 00:12:27.640
photos for two reasons.

00:12:27.640 --> 00:12:30.930
One, to remind you that when we
judge is somebody a giver

00:12:30.930 --> 00:12:33.340
or a taker, are they generous
and helpful, or are they

00:12:33.340 --> 00:12:36.300
selfish, we tend to rely a
lot on intuition, on snap

00:12:36.300 --> 00:12:38.940
judgments, on the thin slices
that Malcolm Gladwell wrote

00:12:38.940 --> 00:12:41.750
about in "Blink." The problem
is these are often wildly

00:12:41.750 --> 00:12:45.720
inaccurate, because somebody's
outer veneer--

00:12:45.720 --> 00:12:46.560
are they friendly?

00:12:46.560 --> 00:12:47.360
Are they warm?

00:12:47.360 --> 00:12:47.835
Are they welcoming?

00:12:47.835 --> 00:12:48.960
Are they polite?--

00:12:48.960 --> 00:12:51.170
is totally different from
their inner motives.

00:12:51.170 --> 00:12:52.900
And Ken Lay is a great example
of this, right?

00:12:52.900 --> 00:12:56.285
He wasn't just a taker, he was a
faker, ie, a taker disguised

00:12:56.285 --> 00:12:57.550
as a giver.

00:12:57.550 --> 00:13:00.660
He donated 1% of Enron's annual
profits to charity.

00:13:00.660 --> 00:13:03.820
He went out of his way to do
what translates from Dutch to

00:13:03.820 --> 00:13:06.300
kissing up, kicking down.

00:13:06.300 --> 00:13:08.460
Takers are really good fakers
when dealing with superiors.

00:13:08.460 --> 00:13:10.240
They want to put their best
feet forward, they want to

00:13:10.240 --> 00:13:12.110
make a good impression
on powerful people.

00:13:12.110 --> 00:13:13.810
But it's hard to maintain
that masquerade at every

00:13:13.810 --> 00:13:14.720
interaction.

00:13:14.720 --> 00:13:18.320
And so even if his bosses were
fooled, oftentimes his peers

00:13:18.320 --> 00:13:20.410
and his subordinates saw
right through him.

00:13:20.410 --> 00:13:22.860
But I believe we didn't have
to go to his peers and

00:13:22.860 --> 00:13:24.970
subordinates to find out
that he was a taker.

00:13:24.970 --> 00:13:27.550
I think we could have looked
at the 1997 Enron annual

00:13:27.550 --> 00:13:30.670
report, four years before the
company collapsed, and spot a

00:13:30.670 --> 00:13:32.550
cue that Ken Lay was a taker.

00:13:32.550 --> 00:13:35.820
Let me show you these
photos in context.

00:13:35.820 --> 00:13:37.910
Here's Huntsman's
photo from his

00:13:37.910 --> 00:13:40.070
company's 2006 annual report.

00:13:40.070 --> 00:13:44.130
What do you think Ken Lay's
photo looked like?

00:13:44.130 --> 00:13:45.630
Some people are saying
it's a little bigger.

00:13:45.630 --> 00:13:47.640
That would be a dramatic
understatement.

00:13:47.640 --> 00:13:51.145
Because if you look at the Enron
1997 annual report, you

00:13:51.145 --> 00:13:53.470
will notice that his head
is an entire page.

00:13:53.470 --> 00:13:56.680
AUDIENCE:
[LAUGHTER AND GROANING]

00:13:56.680 --> 00:14:03.150
ADAM GRANT: Now, lest you think
this is just sort of a

00:14:03.150 --> 00:14:07.135
fun, unusual example, an
outlier, when Chatterjee and

00:14:07.135 --> 00:14:09.510
Hambrick did their research,
they got data on over 100

00:14:09.510 --> 00:14:10.980
computer companies.

00:14:10.980 --> 00:14:13.550
They got Wall Street analysts
who knew the CEOs of each of

00:14:13.550 --> 00:14:16.690
those companies to rate how
much of a taker is each of

00:14:16.690 --> 00:14:17.760
those CEOs.

00:14:17.760 --> 00:14:18.660
How egotistical?

00:14:18.660 --> 00:14:19.580
How selfish?

00:14:19.580 --> 00:14:21.070
How narcissistic?

00:14:21.070 --> 00:14:23.170
And then they looked for cues
that correlated with the Wall

00:14:23.170 --> 00:14:24.400
Street analyst's ratings.

00:14:24.400 --> 00:14:27.620
And they found three cues that
actually correlated at 0.86, a

00:14:27.620 --> 00:14:30.110
whopping correlation in the
social sciences, with the

00:14:30.110 --> 00:14:31.790
ratings given by the analysts.

00:14:31.790 --> 00:14:34.150
And one of them was the
prominence of the CEO's photo

00:14:34.150 --> 00:14:35.600
in the annual report.

00:14:35.600 --> 00:14:38.110
The taker CEOs actually
had larger photos.

00:14:38.110 --> 00:14:40.510
They were more likely to be
pictured alone, as well.

00:14:40.510 --> 00:14:42.080
Which sent a clear
message, right?

00:14:42.080 --> 00:14:43.980
I am the most important person
in this company.

00:14:43.980 --> 00:14:46.450
It is all about me.

00:14:46.450 --> 00:14:47.360
Second cue--

00:14:47.360 --> 00:14:48.310
compensation.

00:14:48.310 --> 00:14:51.480
The average computer industry
CEO made about two to two and

00:14:51.480 --> 00:14:55.080
a half times the annual salary
of the next highest paid

00:14:55.080 --> 00:14:56.760
executive in that company.

00:14:56.760 --> 00:15:00.620
The average taker CEO had a
multiple of what greater than

00:15:00.620 --> 00:15:03.190
the next highest paid executive
in the company?

00:15:03.190 --> 00:15:04.010
AUDIENCE: 40.

00:15:04.010 --> 00:15:04.860
ADAM GRANT: 40.

00:15:04.860 --> 00:15:06.745
I mean, I'm not even sure if
that's financially possible.

00:15:06.745 --> 00:15:08.600
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:15:08.600 --> 00:15:10.210
ADAM GRANT: It was a
multiple of seven.

00:15:10.210 --> 00:15:13.060
So taker CEOs got paid about
seven times more than anybody

00:15:13.060 --> 00:15:14.530
else in their company.

00:15:14.530 --> 00:15:16.180
Third cue was in their speech.

00:15:16.180 --> 00:15:18.970
Not just larger photos, not
just bigger relative pay.

00:15:18.970 --> 00:15:22.190
What two words do taker CEOs
use more than the others?

00:15:22.190 --> 00:15:23.310
AUDIENCE: "I" and "me?"

00:15:23.310 --> 00:15:24.240
ADAM GRANT: "I" and
"me," bingo.

00:15:24.240 --> 00:15:26.010
When talking about the company,
as opposed to "us"

00:15:26.010 --> 00:15:28.140
and we." So those are a
couple ways that you

00:15:28.140 --> 00:15:29.600
could recognize a taker.

00:15:29.600 --> 00:15:31.900
What I want to do, though, is
I want to ask, OK, what

00:15:31.900 --> 00:15:33.420
happens to takers?

00:15:33.420 --> 00:15:34.100
Do they rise?

00:15:34.100 --> 00:15:35.030
Do they fall?

00:15:35.030 --> 00:15:38.040
How does their success compare
to givers and matchers?

00:15:38.040 --> 00:15:41.180
And when I started trying to ask
this question, I began at

00:15:41.180 --> 00:15:45.110
the bottom of success, asking
which group is worst off.

00:15:45.110 --> 00:15:46.190
Who gets the worst results?

00:15:46.190 --> 00:15:49.170
Is it the takers, the givers,
or the matchers?

00:15:49.170 --> 00:15:50.940
And it looked at research
in three domains.

00:15:50.940 --> 00:15:52.800
First, engineers.

00:15:52.800 --> 00:15:54.660
Got to have engineers.

00:15:54.660 --> 00:15:57.680
Stanford's Frank Flynn did this
great study where he got

00:15:57.680 --> 00:16:00.120
engineers to rate each other
on how many favors they did

00:16:00.120 --> 00:16:02.460
versus how many they got,
and then tracked their

00:16:02.460 --> 00:16:05.030
productivity and the number
of errors they made.

00:16:05.030 --> 00:16:07.520
And then medical students.

00:16:07.520 --> 00:16:09.970
Filip Lievens and his colleagues
got every medical

00:16:09.970 --> 00:16:12.290
student in Belgium over a seven
year period to fill out

00:16:12.290 --> 00:16:15.640
surveys about how much they
liked helping others and then

00:16:15.640 --> 00:16:16.700
tracked their grades.

00:16:16.700 --> 00:16:20.700
And then Dane Barnes and I
actually studied salespeople.

00:16:20.700 --> 00:16:24.710
And we were interested
in revenue.

00:16:24.710 --> 00:16:26.640
So who were the highest
producing salespeople who

00:16:26.640 --> 00:16:28.800
bring in the most revenue
every year?

00:16:28.800 --> 00:16:31.520
Across these three groups, the
same results came out.

00:16:31.520 --> 00:16:35.840
The engineers, the medical
students, and the salespeople.

00:16:35.840 --> 00:16:37.760
There was one group, either the
takers, the givers, or the

00:16:37.760 --> 00:16:40.220
matchers, who was consistently
worse off when it came to

00:16:40.220 --> 00:16:43.810
productivity, errors,
grades, and revenue.

00:16:43.810 --> 00:16:46.230
Get a show of hands to see
where your intuitions and

00:16:46.230 --> 00:16:47.680
assumptions lie.

00:16:47.680 --> 00:16:49.230
How many people think
it was the takers at

00:16:49.230 --> 00:16:51.635
the bottom most often?

00:16:51.635 --> 00:16:54.330
All right, we have some
optimists in the room.

00:16:54.330 --> 00:16:57.580
How many people think
it was the matchers?

00:16:57.580 --> 00:16:58.870
OK, a lot of you.

00:16:58.870 --> 00:17:01.320
Now, this is an odd thing
to vote for, because

00:17:01.320 --> 00:17:03.480
statistically if most people
are matchers, it would

00:17:03.480 --> 00:17:05.359
actually be quite hard for
most people to be at the

00:17:05.359 --> 00:17:07.310
bottom of any metric.

00:17:07.310 --> 00:17:08.020
What about the givers?

00:17:08.020 --> 00:17:10.620
How many people think the givers
are at the bottom?

00:17:10.620 --> 00:17:11.940
All right, those of you
with your hands up,

00:17:11.940 --> 00:17:14.050
you would be correct.

00:17:14.050 --> 00:17:15.569
If you looked at the engineers,
the engineers with

00:17:15.569 --> 00:17:17.960
the worst productivity and the
most mistakes were those who

00:17:17.960 --> 00:17:19.960
did a lot more favors
than they got back.

00:17:19.960 --> 00:17:21.490
They were so busy helping
their colleagues, they

00:17:21.490 --> 00:17:24.550
couldn't get their work done
efficiently or effectively.

00:17:24.550 --> 00:17:25.540
Medical students.

00:17:25.540 --> 00:17:27.589
The students with the worst
grades in year one of medical

00:17:27.589 --> 00:17:30.200
school were the ones who agreed
most strongly with

00:17:30.200 --> 00:17:34.280
statements like, I love
helping others.

00:17:34.280 --> 00:17:36.140
Now, if you carry that to
its logical extreme--

00:17:36.140 --> 00:17:37.900
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:17:37.900 --> 00:17:39.420
ADAM GRANT: The doctor that
you trust is somebody who

00:17:39.420 --> 00:17:42.020
never wanted to help anyone.

00:17:42.020 --> 00:17:42.700
Salespeople.

00:17:42.700 --> 00:17:44.830
Dane and I found that the
salespeople with the lowest

00:17:44.830 --> 00:17:48.110
revenue were the ones also who
were passionately motivated to

00:17:48.110 --> 00:17:49.980
help their colleagues and
help their customers.

00:17:49.980 --> 00:17:52.350
And I had one salespeople put
it to me pretty bluntly.

00:17:52.350 --> 00:17:55.380
He said, look, I really want
to help my customers, which

00:17:55.380 --> 00:17:56.745
means I will never sell
them a product.

00:18:00.610 --> 00:18:03.350
So I found this to
be interesting.

00:18:03.350 --> 00:18:05.920
I also found it, for those of
you who are givers, to be a

00:18:05.920 --> 00:18:06.510
little bit sad.

00:18:06.510 --> 00:18:08.440
How many of you would
self-identify more as a giver

00:18:08.440 --> 00:18:11.600
than a matcher or a taker?

00:18:11.600 --> 00:18:13.765
OK, how many of you
self-identify as a giver but

00:18:13.765 --> 00:18:15.390
didn't want to raise your hand
because you feel like that

00:18:15.390 --> 00:18:16.180
violates humility?

00:18:16.180 --> 00:18:17.620
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:18:17.620 --> 00:18:18.600
ADAM GRANT: All right,
those are the real

00:18:18.600 --> 00:18:20.920
givers in the room.

00:18:20.920 --> 00:18:23.710
So I did think this was sad,
though, for those people who

00:18:23.710 --> 00:18:24.440
are givers.

00:18:24.440 --> 00:18:26.550
And so then I wanted to
know who's at the top.

00:18:26.550 --> 00:18:29.230
If the givers are at the bottom,
then who's the most

00:18:29.230 --> 00:18:31.330
likely to have the highest
productivity, the fewest

00:18:31.330 --> 00:18:34.560
mistakes, the best grades,
and, ultimately, the most

00:18:34.560 --> 00:18:35.780
revenue and sales?

00:18:35.780 --> 00:18:37.140
Get a show of hands on
this one as well.

00:18:37.140 --> 00:18:38.580
How many people think
the takers were most

00:18:38.580 --> 00:18:41.090
likely at the top?

00:18:41.090 --> 00:18:42.530
How many people think the
matchers are most likely at

00:18:42.530 --> 00:18:45.110
the top, ignoring my warning
that the most common can't be

00:18:45.110 --> 00:18:48.580
overrepresented in one
part of the spectrum?

00:18:48.580 --> 00:18:50.290
How many people didn't raise
their hand for either the

00:18:50.290 --> 00:18:52.540
takers or the matchers
just now?

00:18:52.540 --> 00:18:55.630
OK, good, now we have
everyone involved.

00:18:55.630 --> 00:18:57.260
Maybe you didn't raise your
hand because you already

00:18:57.260 --> 00:18:59.860
anticipated the thing that took
me 10 years to figure

00:18:59.860 --> 00:19:02.590
out, which is it's
the givers again.

00:19:02.590 --> 00:19:04.620
The givers are not only
overrepresented at the bottom,

00:19:04.620 --> 00:19:07.210
they're also more common
at the top.

00:19:07.210 --> 00:19:09.450
The engineers not only with the
worst results but also the

00:19:09.450 --> 00:19:11.390
best results are the ones
who do a lot more favors

00:19:11.390 --> 00:19:12.920
than they get back.

00:19:12.920 --> 00:19:14.550
The takers and the matchers are
more likely to be in the

00:19:14.550 --> 00:19:15.650
middle when it comes to
their productivity

00:19:15.650 --> 00:19:17.120
and their error rates.

00:19:17.120 --> 00:19:20.160
Medical students with the best
grades, not just in year one

00:19:20.160 --> 00:19:22.780
but over a seven year period are
also the ones who say, I

00:19:22.780 --> 00:19:24.620
love helping others.

00:19:24.620 --> 00:19:26.890
And by the way, the medical
students seem to get better

00:19:26.890 --> 00:19:29.800
over time when they're givers,
because you move from

00:19:29.800 --> 00:19:32.520
basically having to study
information independently to

00:19:32.520 --> 00:19:37.040
collaborating with fellow
physicians and also having to

00:19:37.040 --> 00:19:38.110
work closely with patients.

00:19:38.110 --> 00:19:40.870
And givers tend to really shine
in interdependent work,

00:19:40.870 --> 00:19:42.245
whereas they may struggle
a little bit more

00:19:42.245 --> 00:19:43.700
in independent work.

00:19:43.700 --> 00:19:46.420
In sales, Dane and I found that
giver salespeople who

00:19:46.420 --> 00:19:48.680
really loved helping colleagues
and customers

00:19:48.680 --> 00:19:51.510
actually brought in about 50%
more annual revenue than the

00:19:51.510 --> 00:19:53.150
takers and the matchers.

00:19:53.150 --> 00:19:54.930
So for me, that posed
two questions.

00:19:54.930 --> 00:19:58.220
One was, what do successful
givers do that the rest of us

00:19:58.220 --> 00:20:00.150
takers and matchers might
want to learn?

00:20:00.150 --> 00:20:01.830
And I think this is an exciting
question because

00:20:01.830 --> 00:20:04.340
these reciprocity styles
are not hard wired.

00:20:04.340 --> 00:20:05.440
They're not fixed.

00:20:05.440 --> 00:20:07.180
In fact, they're choices
we make in every single

00:20:07.180 --> 00:20:08.240
interaction.

00:20:08.240 --> 00:20:10.190
As a thought experiment,
think about the next

00:20:10.190 --> 00:20:11.520
person that you meet.

00:20:11.520 --> 00:20:13.610
And you could say, I'm going
to ask myself, do I want to

00:20:13.610 --> 00:20:16.040
just try to help this person
with no strings attached?

00:20:16.040 --> 00:20:18.210
Do I want to try to get
something from this person?

00:20:18.210 --> 00:20:19.990
Or do I want to make
an even trade?

00:20:19.990 --> 00:20:22.120
And the more that you make
those choices, the more

00:20:22.120 --> 00:20:24.810
obviously you define yourself
by one style or another.

00:20:24.810 --> 00:20:25.920
But because it's a choice, it's

00:20:25.920 --> 00:20:27.190
something we can all change.

00:20:27.190 --> 00:20:29.810
And maybe there are ways that
successful givers operate that

00:20:29.810 --> 00:20:31.550
would be interesting
and productive

00:20:31.550 --> 00:20:33.140
for takers and matchers.

00:20:33.140 --> 00:20:35.380
Second question that I was
curious about is, what happens

00:20:35.380 --> 00:20:36.850
to those givers at the bottom?

00:20:36.850 --> 00:20:39.220
And if you would like to be a
helpful person or a generous

00:20:39.220 --> 00:20:42.090
person, what are the traps that
you might fall into and

00:20:42.090 --> 00:20:43.860
how do you avoid them?

00:20:43.860 --> 00:20:45.640
Took me a couple hundred
pages to try to

00:20:45.640 --> 00:20:46.490
answer those questions.

00:20:46.490 --> 00:20:48.950
I'm not going to put you all
through that this morning.

00:20:48.950 --> 00:20:51.160
But what I want to do is just
give you a couple highlights

00:20:51.160 --> 00:20:53.630
of some of the things that I
learned that are described in

00:20:53.630 --> 00:20:56.190
more detail in the book.

00:20:56.190 --> 00:20:58.780
Overall, the thing that I was
really interested in is how do

00:20:58.780 --> 00:21:03.150
givers who succeed relate
to the people in their

00:21:03.150 --> 00:21:05.110
organizations or outside
of them?

00:21:05.110 --> 00:21:07.960
And so I end up looking at how
do givers build networks?

00:21:07.960 --> 00:21:09.540
How do they collaborate?

00:21:09.540 --> 00:21:11.850
How do they develop talent
in other people?

00:21:11.850 --> 00:21:14.070
How do they communicate and
influence and negotiate?

00:21:14.070 --> 00:21:16.150
And I'll just give you a couple
of stories and data

00:21:16.150 --> 00:21:19.860
points from a few of those
perspectives, and then we can

00:21:19.860 --> 00:21:21.960
open it up for questions.

00:21:21.960 --> 00:21:23.360
So collaboration.

00:21:23.360 --> 00:21:26.180
How do givers succeed
in collaboration?

00:21:26.180 --> 00:21:28.750
Anybody recognize this man?

00:21:28.750 --> 00:21:31.110
He's known as the genius behind
the most successful

00:21:31.110 --> 00:21:32.840
television show in history.

00:21:32.840 --> 00:21:34.220
AUDIENCE: "Muppets."

00:21:34.220 --> 00:21:36.490
ADAM GRANT: No, but
it's a good guess.

00:21:36.490 --> 00:21:38.380
Probably you've never
heard of him.

00:21:38.380 --> 00:21:41.340
I hadn't heard of him either
when I came across his story.

00:21:41.340 --> 00:21:43.410
Although I later found out that
he invented a word that

00:21:43.410 --> 00:21:45.280
was uttered by my college
roommate every day for four

00:21:45.280 --> 00:21:48.260
years, which made me a
little bit unhappy.

00:21:48.260 --> 00:21:52.350
But this man is known as the
genius behind a really amazing

00:21:52.350 --> 00:21:53.960
television show.

00:21:53.960 --> 00:21:57.080
And he had a pretty
checkered past.

00:21:57.080 --> 00:22:00.020
He was an undergraduate, and he
ended up deciding that he

00:22:00.020 --> 00:22:02.180
was going to sell
a refrigerator.

00:22:02.180 --> 00:22:04.526
And he sold it to a freshman,
and he took the money, and he

00:22:04.526 --> 00:22:06.180
never delivered the
refrigerator.

00:22:06.180 --> 00:22:07.810
And he almost got kicked out of
college for that, and then

00:22:07.810 --> 00:22:10.320
he almost got kicked out again
when he smashed his dorm room

00:22:10.320 --> 00:22:12.450
window with an electric
guitar.

00:22:12.450 --> 00:22:14.320
And his one sort of
crowning moment in

00:22:14.320 --> 00:22:15.950
life was when he was--

00:22:15.950 --> 00:22:18.500
to that point, at least--
elected the president of "The

00:22:18.500 --> 00:22:21.800
Harvard Lampoon." But
then he was--

00:22:21.800 --> 00:22:24.930
actually there was an attempted
overthrow, a coup,

00:22:24.930 --> 00:22:27.450
by his peers because he was
quote "not responsible

00:22:27.450 --> 00:22:28.720
enough."

00:22:28.720 --> 00:22:30.600
And he ended up finishing
college.

00:22:30.600 --> 00:22:33.790
He decided that he was going to
make a living by betting on

00:22:33.790 --> 00:22:36.510
dog racing, greyhound tracks.

00:22:36.510 --> 00:22:39.610
And he spent two weeks holed in
a library trying to develop

00:22:39.610 --> 00:22:43.190
a mathematic, scientific way
of beating the system.

00:22:43.190 --> 00:22:45.340
Unfortunately, he ran out of
money a few days later and had

00:22:45.340 --> 00:22:47.530
to move in with his parents.

00:22:47.530 --> 00:22:50.980
So bad start to his career.

00:22:50.980 --> 00:22:53.200
But somehow he managed to get
a job writing for a little

00:22:53.200 --> 00:22:57.370
show called "Saturday Night
Live" in the 1980s.

00:22:57.370 --> 00:23:00.320
And one point in his "Saturday
Night Live" career-- his name

00:23:00.320 --> 00:23:02.000
is George Meyer, by the way.

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:03.900
George had a decision to make.

00:23:03.900 --> 00:23:05.060
He had two different
guests that were

00:23:05.060 --> 00:23:06.540
coming onto the show.

00:23:06.540 --> 00:23:09.660
One of them, the Material Girl
in the height of her

00:23:09.660 --> 00:23:12.020
fame, in her prime.

00:23:12.020 --> 00:23:15.760
The other we will say perhaps a
less desirable candidate to

00:23:15.760 --> 00:23:18.570
write a sketch for,
Jimmy Breslin.

00:23:18.570 --> 00:23:20.780
And George was trying to
figure out, OK, we need

00:23:20.780 --> 00:23:22.140
sketches for both
of these people.

00:23:22.140 --> 00:23:23.780
They're going to be coming
on the show.

00:23:23.780 --> 00:23:26.920
And everybody's flocking
to write for Madonna.

00:23:26.920 --> 00:23:28.410
Nobody wants to write
for Jimmy Breslin.

00:23:28.410 --> 00:23:30.260
They don't think he's very
fun or entertaining.

00:23:30.260 --> 00:23:32.950
And George says,
you know what?

00:23:32.950 --> 00:23:35.080
One of the best ways to be
successful if you're working

00:23:35.080 --> 00:23:37.100
in a team or a group is to
try to make other people

00:23:37.100 --> 00:23:38.190
successful.

00:23:38.190 --> 00:23:41.010
If "Saturday Night Live" is
better, then I'm going to be

00:23:41.010 --> 00:23:43.140
better off too because
I'm a part of that.

00:23:43.140 --> 00:23:46.040
And so he engages in what gets
called at the National Outdoor

00:23:46.040 --> 00:23:48.210
Leadership School expedition
behavior.

00:23:48.210 --> 00:23:49.720
Basically saying, if you're
going to go and climb a

00:23:49.720 --> 00:23:52.320
mountain, try and put the
mission ahead of your own

00:23:52.320 --> 00:23:54.870
personal interests
and desires.

00:23:54.870 --> 00:23:55.560
And he says, you know what?

00:23:55.560 --> 00:23:58.100
I'm going to submit a few
sketches for Madonna, but I'm

00:23:58.100 --> 00:24:00.730
going to do my best work
for Jimmy Breslin.

00:24:00.730 --> 00:24:03.180
And that's really where my work
is needed, because so few

00:24:03.180 --> 00:24:05.880
people are wanting to contribute
good ideas there.

00:24:05.880 --> 00:24:09.340
And George ends up writing
this amazing skit.

00:24:09.340 --> 00:24:12.530
It's called "Bond Villains on
a Talk Show." And you get to

00:24:12.530 --> 00:24:14.950
see basically Breslin playing
a Bond Villain, and they're

00:24:14.950 --> 00:24:17.530
comparing strategies
for attacking Bond.

00:24:17.530 --> 00:24:20.400
And that ends up basically
inspiring Mike Myers to do the

00:24:20.400 --> 00:24:23.030
"Austin Powers" movies, which
was kind of a cool thing to

00:24:23.030 --> 00:24:24.350
see happen.

00:24:24.350 --> 00:24:27.370
Well, if you look at what
happened to George next, he

00:24:27.370 --> 00:24:29.070
ended up moving out
to Colorado.

00:24:29.070 --> 00:24:30.570
He was working on a
Letterman script.

00:24:30.570 --> 00:24:32.980
It didn't pan out, and he
decided he wanted to do his

00:24:32.980 --> 00:24:34.490
own comedy.

00:24:34.490 --> 00:24:37.070
And he knew he couldn't do it
alone, so he reaches out to a

00:24:37.070 --> 00:24:39.430
bunch of his "Saturday
Night Live" buddies.

00:24:39.430 --> 00:24:42.850
And he was really torn about how
to do this, because for a

00:24:42.850 --> 00:24:44.830
lot of people George is a really
funny guy and he would

00:24:44.830 --> 00:24:45.710
be a threat.

00:24:45.710 --> 00:24:45.870
Right?

00:24:45.870 --> 00:24:48.090
You're working in this zero sum
sort of competitive world

00:24:48.090 --> 00:24:50.180
of comedy, there are
only so many jobs.

00:24:50.180 --> 00:24:52.920
And George is afraid that if
he reaches out to people

00:24:52.920 --> 00:24:55.090
they're not going to help him
because if he succeeds, that

00:24:55.090 --> 00:24:57.140
means they're going to fail.

00:24:57.140 --> 00:24:59.080
But one of the things that
happened when George engaged

00:24:59.080 --> 00:25:01.550
in this kind of expedition
behavior is he showed that he

00:25:01.550 --> 00:25:03.410
was the kind of person who
cared about the group.

00:25:03.410 --> 00:25:05.110
He cared about other
people's interests.

00:25:05.110 --> 00:25:08.100
And as a result, instead of
gunning for him, people wanted

00:25:08.100 --> 00:25:09.260
to support him.

00:25:09.260 --> 00:25:12.030
He kind of established himself
as a giver, and as a result,

00:25:12.030 --> 00:25:14.410
people were kind of rooting
for him when he was doing

00:25:14.410 --> 00:25:16.660
work, and they wanted to feel
like this is the kind of guy

00:25:16.660 --> 00:25:18.480
who deserved to succeed.

00:25:18.480 --> 00:25:20.880
Part of the reason for that is
most people are matchers.

00:25:20.880 --> 00:25:23.290
And if you're a matcher, you
believe in a just world.

00:25:23.290 --> 00:25:25.820
You think what goes around
ought to come around.

00:25:25.820 --> 00:25:28.160
And that means when you see a
taker acting selfishly, you

00:25:28.160 --> 00:25:29.960
want to punish that person.

00:25:29.960 --> 00:25:32.540
Usually that means, Robb Willer
shows at Stanford,

00:25:32.540 --> 00:25:33.150
gossiping--

00:25:33.150 --> 00:25:35.600
sharing negative reputational
information so that takers

00:25:35.600 --> 00:25:38.950
cannot get away with exploiting
other people.

00:25:38.950 --> 00:25:41.600
Just as you can't stand to see
a taker be selfish and get

00:25:41.600 --> 00:25:44.560
away with it, you also, if
you're a matcher, don't like

00:25:44.560 --> 00:25:46.560
to see generous people fail.

00:25:46.560 --> 00:25:48.940
And so when somebody's a giver
and really helpful, you will

00:25:48.940 --> 00:25:52.000
often go on a mission to plot
that person's well being.

00:25:52.000 --> 00:25:54.230
And I think that's exactly what
happened to George Meyer.

00:25:54.230 --> 00:25:56.160
All these colleagues came out of
the woodwork and they said,

00:25:56.160 --> 00:25:57.340
yeah, we'll contribute.

00:25:57.340 --> 00:25:59.320
George wanted to write this
little magazine called "Army

00:25:59.320 --> 00:26:02.250
Man." It was going to be a
parody of the US military.

00:26:02.250 --> 00:26:03.750
And he reached out to all of
these colleagues, and they

00:26:03.750 --> 00:26:06.740
just gave away some of their
best comedy to him for free.

00:26:06.740 --> 00:26:08.740
One of them was a guy
named Jack Handey.

00:26:08.740 --> 00:26:10.750
And he wrote one of his earliest
"Deep Thoughts"

00:26:10.750 --> 00:26:14.070
pieces two years before it ever
appeared on the show for

00:26:14.070 --> 00:26:16.640
George and his little
"Army Man" magazine.

00:26:16.640 --> 00:26:17.540
George puts out the magazine.

00:26:17.540 --> 00:26:19.230
It has all this great
comedy in it.

00:26:19.230 --> 00:26:22.150
It catches the attention of a
guy by the name of Sam Simon,

00:26:22.150 --> 00:26:24.940
and Sam is just about to start
a little TV show called "The

00:26:24.940 --> 00:26:26.500
Simpsons."

00:26:26.500 --> 00:26:29.090
George ends up getting invited
because of this comedy he was

00:26:29.090 --> 00:26:31.780
able to do to "The Simpsons,"
where he becomes an executive

00:26:31.780 --> 00:26:34.830
producer, wins a bunch of Emmys,
ends up contributing to

00:26:34.830 --> 00:26:37.470
a movie that grossed half a
billion dollars, and has a

00:26:37.470 --> 00:26:39.540
pretty good, successful
career.

00:26:39.540 --> 00:26:41.670
What's interesting, though, is
that he contributed to over

00:26:41.670 --> 00:26:44.800
300 "Simpsons" episodes, and
he only took credit as a

00:26:44.800 --> 00:26:46.250
writer on 12 of them.

00:26:46.250 --> 00:26:48.300
And I think this was part
of his giver style.

00:26:48.300 --> 00:26:50.280
But I think one of the things
that Robb Willer points out in

00:26:50.280 --> 00:26:53.350
his research is that groups
reward individual sacrifice.

00:26:53.350 --> 00:26:54.970
And this is one of the ways
that givers succeed in

00:26:54.970 --> 00:26:55.970
collaboration--

00:26:55.970 --> 00:26:59.250
looking for the unpopular tasks
and volunteering for

00:26:59.250 --> 00:27:01.290
them, and showing that they
actually care about the best

00:27:01.290 --> 00:27:02.220
interests of the group.

00:27:02.220 --> 00:27:04.610
And then when it comes time to
determine who should lead, who

00:27:04.610 --> 00:27:06.980
deserves opportunities, those
are the people who get

00:27:06.980 --> 00:27:09.290
rewarded and trusted
and respected.

00:27:09.290 --> 00:27:11.370
So that's one example of the
kind of thing that we see

00:27:11.370 --> 00:27:13.890
givers do successfully
in collaboration.

00:27:13.890 --> 00:27:18.160
Now, some people will look at
this and say, this is crazy.

00:27:18.160 --> 00:27:20.680
This is not something that I
would recommend to somebody

00:27:20.680 --> 00:27:22.570
that I cared about.

00:27:22.570 --> 00:27:26.700
And if this video clip works,
I want to show you my first

00:27:26.700 --> 00:27:31.175
introduction to how most
people view givers.

