00:29:17.310 --> 00:29:18.510
ADAM GRANT: I think that's
how a lot of people

00:29:18.510 --> 00:29:19.650
view givers, right?

00:29:19.650 --> 00:29:20.990
It's a sign of weakness.

00:29:20.990 --> 00:29:23.110
But I actually think it can
be a source of strength.

00:29:23.110 --> 00:29:25.380
And one of the more interesting
ways that plays

00:29:25.380 --> 00:29:28.740
out is to look at how givers
actually communicate.

00:29:28.740 --> 00:29:31.930
I had a chance to get a personal
taste of this.

00:29:31.930 --> 00:29:34.820
A few years ago, shortly after I
finished my doctorate, I was

00:29:34.820 --> 00:29:37.220
asked to teach a group of
Air Force colonels.

00:29:37.220 --> 00:29:39.520
And I was supposed to teach them
how to lead and motivate.

00:29:39.520 --> 00:29:43.050
I was in my mid-20s, and most of
them were in their mid-50s.

00:29:43.050 --> 00:29:45.260
They were just like the guys out
of "Top Gun." Most of them

00:29:45.260 --> 00:29:48.820
had flown thousands of hours
and had these really pretty

00:29:48.820 --> 00:29:52.900
badass nicknames like Stealth
and Gunner and Iceman.

00:29:52.900 --> 00:29:57.140
And I walked in, and I knew that
I needed to establish my

00:29:57.140 --> 00:29:57.850
credentials, right?

00:29:57.850 --> 00:29:59.730
Here was this kid,
half their age.

00:29:59.730 --> 00:30:03.330
And so I started talking a
little bit about my expertise,

00:30:03.330 --> 00:30:05.820
my experience, why I could maybe
share some knowledge

00:30:05.820 --> 00:30:07.460
that would be helpful to them.

00:30:07.460 --> 00:30:10.270
And it was a four-hour
experience, and I got the

00:30:10.270 --> 00:30:12.530
feedback from the
teaching forums.

00:30:12.530 --> 00:30:14.520
And it was pretty
darn painful.

00:30:14.520 --> 00:30:16.000
Some of the comments
have really burned

00:30:16.000 --> 00:30:17.330
themselves into my brain.

00:30:17.330 --> 00:30:21.710
But the one that really stuck
out the most was quote, "More

00:30:21.710 --> 00:30:25.960
knowledge in the audience than
on the podium." It's like,

00:30:25.960 --> 00:30:27.020
that is very sad.

00:30:27.020 --> 00:30:28.380
Thank you.

00:30:28.380 --> 00:30:30.640
The others were nicer, but
they said similar things.

00:30:30.640 --> 00:30:32.650
One person said, gosh,
the professors get

00:30:32.650 --> 00:30:33.920
younger every year.

00:30:33.920 --> 00:30:36.090
How can they possibly know
anything about leadership when

00:30:36.090 --> 00:30:38.980
they've never led, let
alone had a real job.

00:30:38.980 --> 00:30:41.030
And I was like, OK.

00:30:41.030 --> 00:30:43.980
So part of what I realized
there was that I was

00:30:43.980 --> 00:30:46.560
communicating a little bit
more like a taker does.

00:30:46.560 --> 00:30:50.090
Takers try to get respect
by gaining dominance.

00:30:50.090 --> 00:30:51.980
They try to be as confident
as possible.

00:30:51.980 --> 00:30:53.380
They try to make sure
there are not any

00:30:53.380 --> 00:30:54.860
chinks in their armor.

00:30:54.860 --> 00:30:57.260
And they want to make sure, as a
result, that people see them

00:30:57.260 --> 00:30:58.830
very positively.

00:30:58.830 --> 00:31:01.950
And that style didn't feel
very comfortable for me.

00:31:01.950 --> 00:31:04.410
As a professor, at least, I felt
like my job was always to

00:31:04.410 --> 00:31:06.470
listen to students, to learn
from them, and then try to

00:31:06.470 --> 00:31:08.550
figure out what I knew that
might be helpful.

00:31:08.550 --> 00:31:11.890
And so I had another session
with a different group of Air

00:31:11.890 --> 00:31:14.390
Force colonels scheduled before
they decided to fire me

00:31:14.390 --> 00:31:15.440
altogether.

00:31:15.440 --> 00:31:17.990
And this time I decided that
instead of going with the

00:31:17.990 --> 00:31:20.880
really powerful, confident
approach, I would do something

00:31:20.880 --> 00:31:22.700
a little bit more powerless.

00:31:22.700 --> 00:31:25.870
And I opened up by saying, OK,
guys, I know what some of you

00:31:25.870 --> 00:31:26.830
are thinking right now.

00:31:26.830 --> 00:31:28.860
What can I possibly learn
from a professor

00:31:28.860 --> 00:31:29.750
who's 12 years old?

00:31:29.750 --> 00:31:31.210
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:31:31.210 --> 00:31:34.640
ADAM GRANT: And there was
this dead silence.

00:31:34.640 --> 00:31:36.740
And one of the guys I was pretty
sure started to reach

00:31:36.740 --> 00:31:37.420
for his gun.

00:31:37.420 --> 00:31:39.120
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:31:39.120 --> 00:31:41.120
ADAM GRANT: And then they all
started laughing, and one of

00:31:41.120 --> 00:31:42.530
them said, oh, there's
no way you're 12.

00:31:42.530 --> 00:31:43.840
I'm sure you're at least 13.

00:31:43.840 --> 00:31:45.370
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:31:45.370 --> 00:31:47.400
ADAM GRANT: And that sort of
became a running joke for the

00:31:47.400 --> 00:31:48.260
next four hours.

00:31:48.260 --> 00:31:50.190
And I noticed that I had really

00:31:50.190 --> 00:31:51.480
bonded with the audience.

00:31:51.480 --> 00:31:53.600
I think part of it was because
I had called out the elephant

00:31:53.600 --> 00:31:54.540
in the room.

00:31:54.540 --> 00:31:56.010
But afterward when I read
the feedback, it

00:31:56.010 --> 00:31:56.950
was night and day.

00:31:56.950 --> 00:31:59.510
A lot of them said, gosh, it was
a breath of fresh air to

00:31:59.510 --> 00:32:01.410
have a young professor who
could talk about the

00:32:01.410 --> 00:32:03.090
millennial generation.

00:32:03.090 --> 00:32:05.860
And I think that a lot of it--

00:32:05.860 --> 00:32:07.480
I delivered the exact
same material.

00:32:07.480 --> 00:32:09.990
A lot of it was the
vulnerability and humility to

00:32:09.990 --> 00:32:11.560
say, look, I don't have
all the answers.

00:32:11.560 --> 00:32:14.010
And I may not be able to teach
you guys anything.

00:32:14.010 --> 00:32:16.010
And if you look at the data on
this, givers are a lot more

00:32:16.010 --> 00:32:18.590
comfortable doing that
than takers.

00:32:18.590 --> 00:32:21.160
Takers do not want to expose
their weaknesses, whereas

00:32:21.160 --> 00:32:22.900
givers are willing to
communicate in a much more

00:32:22.900 --> 00:32:26.470
authentic and honest, maybe even
self-deprecating way in

00:32:26.470 --> 00:32:28.430
order to form a genuine
connection with the people

00:32:28.430 --> 00:32:30.800
that they're trying
to connect with.

00:32:30.800 --> 00:32:32.860
And I think there's a great
example of this that dates

00:32:32.860 --> 00:32:35.360
back to the mid-1800s.

00:32:35.360 --> 00:32:36.820
Somebody that you may
have heard of, Abe

00:32:36.820 --> 00:32:38.920
Lincoln, was in a debate.

00:32:38.920 --> 00:32:43.340
And his opponent called him
"two-faced." And I think a lot

00:32:43.340 --> 00:32:45.240
of takers would have been
offended by that.

00:32:45.240 --> 00:32:47.960
I think that Lincoln was a
really extraordinary example

00:32:47.960 --> 00:32:50.160
of a giver who was always
looking for other people's

00:32:50.160 --> 00:32:53.060
best interests and how to
pursue and support them.

00:32:53.060 --> 00:32:55.240
And he didn't even really
skip a beat.

00:32:55.240 --> 00:32:57.590
And he said, "You call
me two-faced.

00:32:57.590 --> 00:32:59.750
If I had another face, do you
really think I would wear this

00:32:59.750 --> 00:33:00.020
one?"

00:33:00.020 --> 00:33:03.140
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:33:03.140 --> 00:33:05.380
ADAM GRANT: And it's a great
example of that kind of

00:33:05.380 --> 00:33:09.120
vulnerability and humility that
establishes a connection.

00:33:09.120 --> 00:33:11.100
I think that Lincoln was really
clever about it, too.

00:33:11.100 --> 00:33:13.470
He knew that his appearance was
something easy to laugh

00:33:13.470 --> 00:33:15.980
at, but also that it was not
going to call into question

00:33:15.980 --> 00:33:16.940
his competence.

00:33:16.940 --> 00:33:18.950
And so it was something that
he could easily be a little

00:33:18.950 --> 00:33:20.570
bit vulnerable about.

00:33:20.570 --> 00:33:23.125
There's a classic study that
shows why this works.

00:33:23.125 --> 00:33:26.110
Elliot Aronson in the 1960s
asked people to listen to

00:33:26.110 --> 00:33:28.830
tapes of "Quiz Bowl" experts.

00:33:28.830 --> 00:33:31.080
Some of them were extremely
knowledgeable, others didn't

00:33:31.080 --> 00:33:33.450
really have the answers to the
trivia questions that were

00:33:33.450 --> 00:33:34.830
being posed to them.

00:33:34.830 --> 00:33:36.690
And you're listening to this
tape, you hear this candidate

00:33:36.690 --> 00:33:38.680
answering all these
questions right.

00:33:38.680 --> 00:33:40.640
And then some of the candidates
the tape just ends,

00:33:40.640 --> 00:33:43.150
and then others spill some
coffee on themselves and you

00:33:43.150 --> 00:33:45.280
hear the cup crash and the
person's like, oh my

00:33:45.280 --> 00:33:47.320
gosh, I'm so clumsy.

00:33:47.320 --> 00:33:51.380
And you actually, it turns
out, like and respect the

00:33:51.380 --> 00:33:55.330
"Quiz Bowl" expert more when he
spills coffee on himself.

00:33:55.330 --> 00:33:58.320
So Aronson and his colleagues
call this the pratfall effect.

00:33:58.320 --> 00:34:00.950
And they say, look, we actually
identify with people

00:34:00.950 --> 00:34:02.900
more when they're human.

00:34:02.900 --> 00:34:05.920
But interestingly, it doesn't
work if the person is not

00:34:05.920 --> 00:34:06.970
"Quiz Bowl" competent.

00:34:06.970 --> 00:34:08.650
So if you got most of the
questions wrong and you

00:34:08.650 --> 00:34:13.135
spilled coffee on yourself, you
just look like an idiot.

00:34:13.135 --> 00:34:15.580
But I think that this is a lot
of what happens when givers

00:34:15.580 --> 00:34:16.080
communicate.

00:34:16.080 --> 00:34:17.889
There's some really good
research by Alison Fragale at

00:34:17.889 --> 00:34:20.520
the University of North Carolina
who shows that we

00:34:20.520 --> 00:34:23.030
tend to think that powerful
speech, the confident, the

00:34:23.030 --> 00:34:25.460
assertive, the dominant, is
going to earn us status and

00:34:25.460 --> 00:34:26.989
trust and respect.

00:34:26.989 --> 00:34:28.850
But that that's only true
if you're really working

00:34:28.850 --> 00:34:30.600
independently, separately.

00:34:30.600 --> 00:34:32.810
If you have to collaborate, you
have to work in a team, or

00:34:32.810 --> 00:34:35.630
you have to have clients, you
will actually get more trust

00:34:35.630 --> 00:34:39.980
if you use a lot of ums and uhs
and ifs and hesitations

00:34:39.980 --> 00:34:44.239
and tag lines and qualifiers,
because what happens is when

00:34:44.239 --> 00:34:47.210
you speak in a more tentative,
soft-spoken way, people tend

00:34:47.210 --> 00:34:49.750
to assume that you have their
best interests at heart.

00:34:49.750 --> 00:34:50.250
And guess what?

00:34:50.250 --> 00:34:53.290
In a collaboration, we care at
least as much about whether

00:34:53.290 --> 00:34:55.830
you care about my best interests
as whether you're

00:34:55.830 --> 00:34:58.570
competent and capable
and assertive.

00:34:58.570 --> 00:35:00.420
And again, I think this is
something that often works

00:35:00.420 --> 00:35:02.360
really well for givers
as they communicate.

00:35:02.360 --> 00:35:04.920
This willingness to defer to
other people, to show an

00:35:04.920 --> 00:35:06.800
interest in other people's
opinions

00:35:06.800 --> 00:35:08.940
while they're talking.

00:35:08.940 --> 00:35:10.640
Those are a couple of things
on communication I thought

00:35:10.640 --> 00:35:12.120
were interesting.

00:35:12.120 --> 00:35:14.430
One other thing I wanted
to highlight--

00:35:14.430 --> 00:35:16.250
burnout.

00:35:16.250 --> 00:35:18.260
Teacher burnout.

00:35:18.260 --> 00:35:19.800
Common problem.

00:35:19.800 --> 00:35:21.360
This is Conrey Callahan.

00:35:21.360 --> 00:35:23.010
She was a Teach for America
teacher who probably

00:35:23.010 --> 00:35:25.940
experienced the worst burnout
I've ever seen in a classroom.

00:35:25.940 --> 00:35:28.820
She has at Overbook High School
in Philadelphia where

00:35:28.820 --> 00:35:31.770
the graduation rate is abysmally
low, the crime rate

00:35:31.770 --> 00:35:33.240
is extremely high.

00:35:33.240 --> 00:35:34.900
There are students who actually
only come to school

00:35:34.900 --> 00:35:36.520
two or three days a year.

00:35:36.520 --> 00:35:38.390
And she was just exhausted
by these students

00:35:38.390 --> 00:35:39.840
who wouldn't listen.

00:35:39.840 --> 00:35:43.350
And somehow she managed to turn
that around and actually

00:35:43.350 --> 00:35:46.250
end up getting a National
Teaching Award and stay longer

00:35:46.250 --> 00:35:47.670
with Teach for America
than any of the

00:35:47.670 --> 00:35:49.260
people in her cohort.

00:35:49.260 --> 00:35:52.020
And when I started to interview
her about why, she

00:35:52.020 --> 00:35:53.780
said some things that I thought
tracked really well

00:35:53.780 --> 00:35:55.180
with some recent data.

00:35:55.180 --> 00:35:57.820
The first thing she said was at
the height of her burnout

00:35:57.820 --> 00:36:00.720
she was getting up at 6:00 AM,
she was working 'til 1:00 AM

00:36:00.720 --> 00:36:03.370
usually, she was having to do
grading on the weekends.

00:36:03.370 --> 00:36:06.190
Instead of giving less,
she gave more.

00:36:06.190 --> 00:36:08.190
She started a nonprofit
organization called Minds

00:36:08.190 --> 00:36:10.300
Matter Philadelphia,
where she was

00:36:10.300 --> 00:36:12.690
tutoring kids on the weekends.

00:36:12.690 --> 00:36:14.770
And I was like, how could you
possibly burnout less by

00:36:14.770 --> 00:36:15.340
giving more?

00:36:15.340 --> 00:36:18.350
That, I think, defies every
principle of physics and

00:36:18.350 --> 00:36:20.210
chemistry I've ever learned.

00:36:20.210 --> 00:36:23.110
And she said, well, part of
what happened was in my

00:36:23.110 --> 00:36:25.560
everyday job I don't feel like
I necessarily make a dent.

00:36:25.560 --> 00:36:27.160
I don't think I have
an impact.

00:36:27.160 --> 00:36:29.680
Whereas when I'm working with
these kids on the weekends,

00:36:29.680 --> 00:36:31.770
these are high-achieving
low income kids.

00:36:31.770 --> 00:36:34.145
And I feel like I spend four or
five hours with them, and

00:36:34.145 --> 00:36:35.920
I'm actually helping them
get into college.

00:36:35.920 --> 00:36:38.170
And it renews my hope that
my regular teaching

00:36:38.170 --> 00:36:40.090
job can have an impact.

00:36:40.090 --> 00:36:41.890
And I think it reveals one
of the really interesting

00:36:41.890 --> 00:36:43.570
principles of giver burnout.

00:36:43.570 --> 00:36:45.810
Givers don't burnout just
because they're working too

00:36:45.810 --> 00:36:47.170
hard or giving too much.

00:36:47.170 --> 00:36:48.920
They burnout when they don't
get to feel that they're

00:36:48.920 --> 00:36:51.140
making the difference that
they had set out to make.

00:36:51.140 --> 00:36:53.810
And I think that Conrey's idea
of starting this nonprofit was

00:36:53.810 --> 00:36:56.520
a really interesting way of not
only seeing more of her

00:36:56.520 --> 00:36:58.360
impact by trying to help
people who were really

00:36:58.360 --> 00:37:01.670
dedicated to school, but also
just created sort of a fresh

00:37:01.670 --> 00:37:04.340
experience of being in a
different setting and being

00:37:04.340 --> 00:37:06.510
able to renew a little
bit of energy.

00:37:06.510 --> 00:37:08.860
The other thing she did that I
think was really clever was

00:37:08.860 --> 00:37:11.540
she chunked her giving into
blocks, as opposed to

00:37:11.540 --> 00:37:13.520
sprinkling it out
across the day.

00:37:13.520 --> 00:37:15.980
There's an experiment by Sonja
Lyubomirsky that looks at

00:37:15.980 --> 00:37:17.490
random acts of kindness.

00:37:17.490 --> 00:37:20.790
And you are either randomly
assigned to do one random act

00:37:20.790 --> 00:37:23.850
of kindness every day for a week
or five random acts of

00:37:23.850 --> 00:37:26.480
kindness in one day each week.

00:37:26.480 --> 00:37:29.280
And most people assume that you
should do them every day,

00:37:29.280 --> 00:37:31.190
and that way you feel like
you're helpful every day and

00:37:31.190 --> 00:37:32.640
that will boost your
happiness.

00:37:32.640 --> 00:37:35.270
But Sonja finds the opposite,
that doing five random acts of

00:37:35.270 --> 00:37:37.710
kindness in one day actually
leads to greater happiness

00:37:37.710 --> 00:37:40.740
than doing one each
day for five days.

00:37:40.740 --> 00:37:42.120
We can speculate about
why that is.

00:37:42.120 --> 00:37:44.410
I think this research
is relatively new.

00:37:44.410 --> 00:37:47.550
But one of Sonja's dominant
explanations is that you feel

00:37:47.550 --> 00:37:48.960
like you are actually
having an impact.

00:37:48.960 --> 00:37:51.470
When you do five acts of
meaningful helping a day, they

00:37:51.470 --> 00:37:54.330
add up, whereas when you
sprinkle them around it's sort

00:37:54.330 --> 00:37:56.550
of a drop in the bucket, and it
doesn't make you feel like

00:37:56.550 --> 00:37:59.630
you're truly making
a difference.

00:37:59.630 --> 00:38:01.720
I think that that's a really
interesting practice.

00:38:01.720 --> 00:38:04.300
So there's one Fortune 500
company that actually goes out

00:38:04.300 --> 00:38:07.300
of its way to set quiet time
windows-- this is Leslie

00:38:07.300 --> 00:38:09.400
Perlow's research at Harvard
Business School--

00:38:09.400 --> 00:38:12.475
to say if you are an engineer,
you're constantly interrupting

00:38:12.475 --> 00:38:14.250
and getting interrupted by
your colleagues, and it's

00:38:14.250 --> 00:38:15.900
really hard to get your
own work done.

00:38:15.900 --> 00:38:18.460
So what if Tuesdays, Thursdays,
and Friday mornings

00:38:18.460 --> 00:38:20.990
from 9:00 to 12:00 there were no
interruptions and you could

00:38:20.990 --> 00:38:22.130
get your own work done.

00:38:22.130 --> 00:38:24.150
And then you have these windows
set aside where you

00:38:24.150 --> 00:38:26.090
can be helpful and
support others.

00:38:26.090 --> 00:38:29.210
When Leslie did that, this
particular company had 66% of

00:38:29.210 --> 00:38:31.390
engineers show above average
productivity.

00:38:31.390 --> 00:38:33.900
And at the end of the day they
launched their product, which

00:38:33.900 --> 00:38:36.550
was a laser printer, on time
for only the second time in

00:38:36.550 --> 00:38:37.910
division history.

00:38:37.910 --> 00:38:39.770
And I think this, again,
illustrates some things that

00:38:39.770 --> 00:38:41.600
givers can do to
avoid burnout.

00:38:41.600 --> 00:38:43.350
Don't help all the people
all the time

00:38:43.350 --> 00:38:44.520
with all the requests.

00:38:44.520 --> 00:38:46.820
Don't drop everything to support
the people around you,

00:38:46.820 --> 00:38:48.680
but rather say I'm going to
reserve windows where I'm

00:38:48.680 --> 00:38:50.640
going to be helpful to the
people around me, and then

00:38:50.640 --> 00:38:53.310
also I'm going to have times
that I block out for my own

00:38:53.310 --> 00:38:54.800
individual work.

00:38:54.800 --> 00:38:56.760
Those are some of the things
that I wanted to talk about.

00:38:56.760 --> 00:38:58.880
Just a few other things you
might find in the book if you

00:38:58.880 --> 00:39:00.550
are curious.

00:39:00.550 --> 00:39:02.530
How do givers build networks,
and how do those look

00:39:02.530 --> 00:39:05.770
different from takers
and matchers?

00:39:05.770 --> 00:39:08.100
How does "Fortune's"
best networker--

00:39:08.100 --> 00:39:09.350
the guy, not the cat--

00:39:11.550 --> 00:39:14.370
claim that he built an
extraordinary network?

00:39:14.370 --> 00:39:16.450
Some of you may know this man.

00:39:16.450 --> 00:39:18.760
Just through random
acts of kindness.

00:39:18.760 --> 00:39:21.400
And does it actually work?

00:39:21.400 --> 00:39:22.480
Leadership.

00:39:22.480 --> 00:39:25.850
How does this guy, CJ Skender,
an accounting professor,

00:39:25.850 --> 00:39:29.240
because he's a giver, know
that this woman, Beth

00:39:29.240 --> 00:39:31.720
Traynham, whose own mother told
her she couldn't add or

00:39:31.720 --> 00:39:34.640
tell time, would one day
become a national gold

00:39:34.640 --> 00:39:36.120
medalist in accounting?

00:39:36.120 --> 00:39:38.540
And how did he know that this
guy, Reggie Love, who was

00:39:38.540 --> 00:39:41.480
written off by many as an
athlete, would one day become

00:39:41.480 --> 00:39:43.100
President Obama's body man?

00:39:43.100 --> 00:39:46.040
What do givers know about
spotting talent in others that

00:39:46.040 --> 00:39:48.280
takers and matchers
miss out on?

00:39:48.280 --> 00:39:49.935
Decision making.

00:39:49.935 --> 00:39:52.510
Why does a basketball executive
named Stu Inman pass

00:39:52.510 --> 00:39:55.120
up the chance to choose Michael
Jordan and end up

00:39:55.120 --> 00:39:58.030
getting a draft bust, Sam Bowie,
and then hang on to Sam

00:39:58.030 --> 00:40:01.640
Bowie for four years instead
of cutting his losses?

00:40:01.640 --> 00:40:05.550
What does it take to get other
people to avoid the trap that

00:40:05.550 --> 00:40:07.850
psychologists call escalation
of commitment to a losing

00:40:07.850 --> 00:40:11.110
course of action and instead
say, you know what, it's over

00:40:11.110 --> 00:40:12.050
man, just let her go?

00:40:12.050 --> 00:40:16.510
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER[

00:40:16.510 --> 00:40:18.090
ADAM GRANT: I know sometimes
that one hits a little too

00:40:18.090 --> 00:40:18.700
close to home.

00:40:18.700 --> 00:40:21.520
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:40:21.520 --> 00:40:24.500
ADAM GRANT: And then how do you
avoid being treated as a

00:40:24.500 --> 00:40:25.950
doormat if you're a giver?

00:40:25.950 --> 00:40:27.930
What prevents you from
becoming a pushover?

00:40:27.930 --> 00:40:30.580
How do you deal with a taker and
still maintain your sense

00:40:30.580 --> 00:40:32.580
of concern for others
and generosity?

00:40:32.580 --> 00:40:36.025
But my favorite question, is
it possible to turn a taker

00:40:36.025 --> 00:40:37.680
into a giver?

00:40:37.680 --> 00:40:39.430
Maybe not in all of their
interactions, right?

00:40:39.430 --> 00:40:42.630
But can we nudge people more in
the giving direction in our

00:40:42.630 --> 00:40:44.010
relationships with them?

00:40:44.010 --> 00:40:44.860
Maybe.

00:40:44.860 --> 00:40:46.920
One of my favorite ways to do
that, some of you have been

00:40:46.920 --> 00:40:49.480
part of already, it's called the
reciprocity ring, invented

00:40:49.480 --> 00:40:51.640
by Wayne Baker at the University
of Michigan and

00:40:51.640 --> 00:40:53.220
Cheryl Baker at Humax
Networks.

00:40:53.220 --> 00:40:56.710
The idea is you gather a group
of 10 or 20 or 30 people, and

00:40:56.710 --> 00:40:58.570
you ask them all to
make a request.

00:40:58.570 --> 00:41:01.300
Something meaningful, personal,
or professional that

00:41:01.300 --> 00:41:03.190
they want but can't
get on their own.

00:41:03.190 --> 00:41:04.960
And then you ask everybody else
in the group just to try

00:41:04.960 --> 00:41:06.530
to use their knowledge and their
networks to make the

00:41:06.530 --> 00:41:07.690
request happen.

00:41:07.690 --> 00:41:10.180
And some pretty amazing things
happen when everybody adopts

00:41:10.180 --> 00:41:12.410
the norm of giving and says,
we're just going to all try to

00:41:12.410 --> 00:41:13.300
support each other.

00:41:13.300 --> 00:41:14.840
Couple examples.

00:41:14.840 --> 00:41:19.810
Earlier this year a woman came
in said, my hero is a man

00:41:19.810 --> 00:41:22.430
who's a blogger, but he's
also a minimalist.

00:41:22.430 --> 00:41:24.640
And he's impossible to
contact because he

00:41:24.640 --> 00:41:25.990
likes a simple life.

00:41:25.990 --> 00:41:29.140
I've wanted for six years to
meet him and one, thank him,

00:41:29.140 --> 00:41:31.050
and two, ask him how
I can help him.

00:41:31.050 --> 00:41:32.210
But I don't know how to
get in touch with him.

00:41:32.210 --> 00:41:33.490
Could anybody help me?

00:41:33.490 --> 00:41:35.670
And one person in this room
says, yeah, you know what?

00:41:35.670 --> 00:41:37.560
I know a blogger
who knows him.

00:41:37.560 --> 00:41:39.570
And they've been introduced,
and they're meeting up for

00:41:39.570 --> 00:41:40.780
dinner next week.

00:41:40.780 --> 00:41:43.060
I'm very excited to
see how it goes.

00:41:43.060 --> 00:41:44.690
I think it probably wouldn't
have happened unless she had

00:41:44.690 --> 00:41:46.780
access to this network of people
who in that moment were

00:41:46.780 --> 00:41:48.160
willing to act like givers.

00:41:48.160 --> 00:41:48.740
And guess what?

00:41:48.740 --> 00:41:50.860
Because the requests are
visible, it's really hard to

00:41:50.860 --> 00:41:51.650
be a taker.

00:41:51.650 --> 00:41:53.930
Because when you make that ask,
if you don't help other

00:41:53.930 --> 00:41:57.590
people, nobody wants
to support you.

00:41:57.590 --> 00:41:59.250
There are a few people in this
room who were present for this

00:41:59.250 --> 00:42:01.380
particular request in my
classroom when a student named

00:42:01.380 --> 00:42:04.680
Michelle said she had a friend
who had her growth stunted as

00:42:04.680 --> 00:42:07.500
a child and she could never find
the right clothing, could

00:42:07.500 --> 00:42:08.550
anybody help her?

00:42:08.550 --> 00:42:10.540
And another student, Jessica,
raised her hand, and she said,

00:42:10.540 --> 00:42:12.700
yeah, I have an uncle in
the garment business.

00:42:12.700 --> 00:42:14.490
And I'm happy to reach
out to him.

00:42:14.490 --> 00:42:16.100
And three months later,
custom clothing

00:42:16.100 --> 00:42:17.780
arrived on her doorstep.

00:42:17.780 --> 00:42:20.400
And for the first time in the
life of Hope, Michelle's

00:42:20.400 --> 00:42:23.480
friend, she actually had
clothing that fit her right.

00:42:23.480 --> 00:42:25.620
My favorite request, though,
of all time was a student

00:42:25.620 --> 00:42:28.780
named Alex who came in one day
we were running one of these

00:42:28.780 --> 00:42:30.720
reciprocity ring exercises.

00:42:30.720 --> 00:42:34.230
And he said, I think the closest
thing to nirvana in

00:42:34.230 --> 00:42:36.520
life is riding a
roller coaster.

00:42:36.520 --> 00:42:39.340
And I came to Wharton because I
one day would love to run a

00:42:39.340 --> 00:42:40.960
place like Six Flags.

00:42:40.960 --> 00:42:43.160
But strangely, Six Flags does
not recruit at the Wharton

00:42:43.160 --> 00:42:45.030
School of Business.

00:42:45.030 --> 00:42:47.000
So could anybody help me figure
out how to break into

00:42:47.000 --> 00:42:48.500
the industry?

00:42:48.500 --> 00:42:50.140
Another student, Andrew, raises
his hand and says,

00:42:50.140 --> 00:42:52.840
yeah, I think my dad knows the
ex-CEO, I'm happy to get you

00:42:52.840 --> 00:42:53.940
guys in touch.

00:42:53.940 --> 00:42:56.710
Two weeks later, they have a
cell conversation, and Alex

00:42:56.710 --> 00:42:57.870
comes into class the next day.

00:42:57.870 --> 00:42:59.790
I'm so excited to find
out about it.

00:42:59.790 --> 00:43:00.810
So Alex, how'd it go?

00:43:00.810 --> 00:43:02.910
And Alex was like, I learned
something really important

00:43:02.910 --> 00:43:04.030
from that conversation--

00:43:04.030 --> 00:43:06.070
I will never want to work
in that industry ever.

00:43:06.070 --> 00:43:08.070
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:43:08.070 --> 00:43:10.920
ADAM GRANT: And I was like, OK,
at least you were able to

00:43:10.920 --> 00:43:11.980
rule that out.

00:43:11.980 --> 00:43:14.070
And because of that, I am proud
to say that today, at

00:43:14.070 --> 00:43:16.830
this very moment, Alex is
living his dream happily

00:43:16.830 --> 00:43:18.085
employed as a management
consultant.

00:43:18.085 --> 00:43:21.650
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:43:21.650 --> 00:43:23.520
ADAM GRANT: Anyway, I'm
happy to talk further.

00:43:23.520 --> 00:43:26.340
If you check out the "Give and
Take" site, you can rate

00:43:26.340 --> 00:43:28.810
yourself on a survey and figure
out do you tend to

00:43:28.810 --> 00:43:31.370
think most like a giver,
a taker, or a matcher?

00:43:31.370 --> 00:43:34.070
Although you all know too much
now, so your ratings will be

00:43:34.070 --> 00:43:35.260
fatally flawed.

00:43:35.260 --> 00:43:37.030
There's also a 360 assessment.

00:43:37.030 --> 00:43:39.440
You can anonymously ask anybody
who knows who to rate

00:43:39.440 --> 00:43:42.400
you, and then basically find out
do I see myself the same

00:43:42.400 --> 00:43:43.850
way other people see me?

00:43:43.850 --> 00:43:46.190
And then there's also a Nominate
a Giver feature, sort

00:43:46.190 --> 00:43:48.440
of like a bigger version of
the way that peer and spot

00:43:48.440 --> 00:43:51.200
bonuses often work, where you
can write a little paragraph

00:43:51.200 --> 00:43:52.450
to recognize somebody
that you think

00:43:52.450 --> 00:43:53.610
has been really generous.

00:43:53.610 --> 00:43:55.990
And we're going to basically
recognize one a week based on

00:43:55.990 --> 00:43:58.890
voting for the best example
of a successful giver.

00:43:58.890 --> 00:44:00.780
All right, happy to open
it up for questions.

00:44:00.780 --> 00:44:02.930
Who's the first victim?

00:44:02.930 --> 00:44:05.430
Tina, "Is there a difference
between men and women?" In

00:44:05.430 --> 00:44:08.160
general, or in "Give
and Take?"

00:44:08.160 --> 00:44:09.360
AUDIENCE: "Give and Take."

00:44:09.360 --> 00:44:11.110
ADAM GRANT: Yeah.

00:44:11.110 --> 00:44:13.780
I really try to avoid this
question, because I wanted to

00:44:13.780 --> 00:44:15.970
write about people,
not sort of divide

00:44:15.970 --> 00:44:17.010
the world by genders.

00:44:17.010 --> 00:44:19.720
But the data on this I think
are pretty interesting.

00:44:19.720 --> 00:44:22.280
So Alice Eagly and her
colleagues have meta-analyzed

00:44:22.280 --> 00:44:25.030
about three decades of studies
looking at are men or women

00:44:25.030 --> 00:44:26.820
more likely to help others?

00:44:26.820 --> 00:44:28.660
And they find that the answer
is no, they're actually

00:44:28.660 --> 00:44:31.280
equally likely to be helpful,
but that they specialize in

00:44:31.280 --> 00:44:32.950
helping in different domains.

00:44:32.950 --> 00:44:34.820
So women tend to do more helping
behaviors in close

00:44:34.820 --> 00:44:35.890
relationships.

00:44:35.890 --> 00:44:37.930
They spend more time helping
their friends, their family

00:44:37.930 --> 00:44:39.720
members, and their
close colleagues.

00:44:39.720 --> 00:44:41.720
Whereas men are more likely,
it seems from the data, to

00:44:41.720 --> 00:44:45.030
help strangers, especially in
emergency situations, which I

00:44:45.030 --> 00:44:48.010
think has an interesting
macho implication.

00:44:48.010 --> 00:44:50.380
Oh, I must be tough and
rescue someone now.

00:44:50.380 --> 00:44:52.050
Arrr.

00:44:52.050 --> 00:44:55.140
But I think a lot of people
stereotype women as being more

00:44:55.140 --> 00:44:57.460
likely to be givers because a
lot of the most important

00:44:57.460 --> 00:44:59.490
giving that happens in the
world is the close

00:44:59.490 --> 00:45:01.890
relationship based giving, and
I would love to see more men

00:45:01.890 --> 00:45:03.590
acting like women.

00:45:03.590 --> 00:45:06.180
AUDIENCE: So you said that for
givers, they're at the bottom

00:45:06.180 --> 00:45:07.800
and then at the top.

00:45:07.800 --> 00:45:10.530
Has that been filtered out
by intelligence level?

00:45:10.530 --> 00:45:13.300
So I'm wondering if you get to
a point where things become

00:45:13.300 --> 00:45:16.050
too easy so you start helping
people if you're at the top

00:45:16.050 --> 00:45:18.780
versus for some people it might
be you just help because

00:45:18.780 --> 00:45:20.180
you know that's something
you can do.

00:45:20.180 --> 00:45:20.740
ADAM GRANT: Yeah.

00:45:20.740 --> 00:45:22.550
So intelligence is a really
interesting question.

00:45:22.550 --> 00:45:25.430
In my data, intelligence are
close to orthogonal--

00:45:25.430 --> 00:45:28.450
intelligence measures are to
"Give and Take." So you can

00:45:28.450 --> 00:45:31.990
find very, very bright givers,
very bright takers.

00:45:31.990 --> 00:45:32.760
There is some evidence.

00:45:32.760 --> 00:45:35.200
Russell James, an economist, has
actually shown the smarter

00:45:35.200 --> 00:45:37.490
you are, the more you give
to charity, even after

00:45:37.490 --> 00:45:40.050
controlling for your education
levels, your

00:45:40.050 --> 00:45:42.050
socioeconomic status.

00:45:42.050 --> 00:45:46.070
And the idea is basically that
if you're incredibly high in

00:45:46.070 --> 00:45:48.930
intellectual horsepower, it's
easier for you to appreciate

00:45:48.930 --> 00:45:51.010
all the different ways that you
could be benefiting others

00:45:51.010 --> 00:45:52.550
in the long run.

00:45:52.550 --> 00:45:54.340
I think there's a lot
a debate about it.

00:45:54.340 --> 00:45:55.470
But there's another study
by [? Millet and ?]

00:45:55.470 --> 00:45:57.490
DeWitt that actually shows that
when you give people an

00:45:57.490 --> 00:45:59.800
intelligence test and then you
ask them to play a prisoner's

00:45:59.800 --> 00:46:01.680
dilemma game where they have to
keep money for themselves

00:46:01.680 --> 00:46:03.680
or give it to others, the
smarter you are, the more you

00:46:03.680 --> 00:46:05.340
give to others.

00:46:05.340 --> 00:46:07.530
That being said, the
correlations are so small that

00:46:07.530 --> 00:46:10.010
I don't think they're
practically that meaningful.

00:46:10.010 --> 00:46:12.110
In the studies that Dane and I
did of salespeople we actually

00:46:12.110 --> 00:46:14.390
controlled for intelligence
and found that even after

00:46:14.390 --> 00:46:16.910
taking that out of the equation
the giver factor was

00:46:16.910 --> 00:46:18.820
basically a very strong
predictor of both hitting the

00:46:18.820 --> 00:46:21.120
bottom and the top
of sales revenue.

00:46:21.120 --> 00:46:23.300
The other intelligence data
point that I've seen is

00:46:23.300 --> 00:46:25.620
there's a great study by Kim and
Glomb called "Get Smarty

00:46:25.620 --> 00:46:28.660
Pants" which shows the smarter
you are, the more likely you

00:46:28.660 --> 00:46:30.660
are to be bullied by your
colleagues who are jealous,

00:46:30.660 --> 00:46:31.880
unless you're a giver.

00:46:31.880 --> 00:46:34.050
And that goes back to the point
we want to take down

00:46:34.050 --> 00:46:36.510
really bright, successful
takers, but we want to support

00:46:36.510 --> 00:46:39.680
and lift up the bright,
successful givers.

00:46:39.680 --> 00:46:41.380
Next question.

00:46:41.380 --> 00:46:41.530
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:46:41.530 --> 00:46:41.890
[INAUDIBLE]

00:46:41.890 --> 00:46:42.930
things I loved for
the session.

00:46:42.930 --> 00:46:44.390
It was really interesting.

00:46:44.390 --> 00:46:46.820
Going back to the point of
showing vulnerability

00:46:46.820 --> 00:46:49.680
publicly, I was wondering
if that changes

00:46:49.680 --> 00:46:51.140
from culture to culture.

00:46:51.140 --> 00:46:54.030
Because in certain cultures I
have the feeling that the more

00:46:54.030 --> 00:46:57.070
senior or the more professional
you are,

00:46:57.070 --> 00:46:59.360
[? public ?] vulnerability might
be seen as something

00:46:59.360 --> 00:47:00.720
quite [? narrative ?]
intellectually.

00:47:00.720 --> 00:47:02.490
ADAM GRANT: Yeah, I think
there's a huge cross-cultural

00:47:02.490 --> 00:47:04.070
difference there.

00:47:04.070 --> 00:47:05.970
One of the best ways, I think,
to think about that is to go

00:47:05.970 --> 00:47:09.030
back to Hofstede's classic
research on power distance and

00:47:09.030 --> 00:47:12.180
say that in cultures where
people accept basically steep

00:47:12.180 --> 00:47:15.610
hierarchies as appropriate and
correct, it's a little bit

00:47:15.610 --> 00:47:17.720
riskier to open up and
be vulnerable.

00:47:17.720 --> 00:47:19.800
I also think, though, that that
was maybe the situations

00:47:19.800 --> 00:47:22.090
where it's most powerful and
disarming for somebody that

00:47:22.090 --> 00:47:25.720
you expect to have this
incredibly polished

00:47:25.720 --> 00:47:28.990
presentation style to actually
open up and say, look, I'm

00:47:28.990 --> 00:47:30.700
just human, too.

00:47:30.700 --> 00:47:33.300
Aronson's research actually
showed that it will depend on

00:47:33.300 --> 00:47:35.380
the audience, though, how
people react to it.

00:47:35.380 --> 00:47:38.550
So the people who like those
who sort of spill coffee on

00:47:38.550 --> 00:47:41.010
themselves or stumble the most
are those with average

00:47:41.010 --> 00:47:42.280
self-esteem.

00:47:42.280 --> 00:47:43.890
Those are the people who see
themselves as human, and they

00:47:43.890 --> 00:47:45.300
like other people to be human.

00:47:45.300 --> 00:47:47.240
Whereas if you have really high
self-esteem, you tend to

00:47:47.240 --> 00:47:50.010
want other people to appear
really confident.

00:47:50.010 --> 00:47:52.160
If you have low self-esteem,
you just

00:47:52.160 --> 00:47:53.472
don't like other people.

00:47:53.472 --> 00:47:55.280
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:47:55.280 --> 00:47:58.260
ADAM GRANT: That may be a slight
caricature of the data.

00:47:58.260 --> 00:47:58.780
AUDIENCE: Hey, Adam.

00:47:58.780 --> 00:48:01.090
Katie Everett, fellow
Harvard diver.

00:48:01.090 --> 00:48:01.970
Hi.

00:48:01.970 --> 00:48:03.430
I am wondering--

00:48:03.430 --> 00:48:05.840
I have my daughter here today,
