00:48:11.050 --> 00:48:14.640
foster this kind of mindset
in your children?

00:48:14.640 --> 00:48:17.510
I'm just wondering if you have
any insights into how to do

00:48:17.510 --> 00:48:18.630
something like that.

00:48:18.630 --> 00:48:18.970
ADAM GRANT: Yeah.

00:48:18.970 --> 00:48:20.990
First of all, I think it should
be called give your

00:48:20.990 --> 00:48:22.600
child to work day, not take.

00:48:22.600 --> 00:48:23.048
No.

00:48:23.048 --> 00:48:25.740
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:48:25.740 --> 00:48:26.840
ADAM GRANT: I was working
on that all night.

00:48:26.840 --> 00:48:29.205
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:48:29.205 --> 00:48:29.680
ADAM GRANT: No.

00:48:29.680 --> 00:48:32.260
I think that it's a really
interesting question.

00:48:32.260 --> 00:48:34.010
As an organizational
psychologist rather than a

00:48:34.010 --> 00:48:36.700
developmental psychologist, it
really stretches far beyond my

00:48:36.700 --> 00:48:37.310
areas of expertise.

00:48:37.310 --> 00:48:39.530
So I'm more of a consumer
in this area

00:48:39.530 --> 00:48:40.780
than I think a producer.

00:48:40.780 --> 00:48:43.030
But I've had a lot of fun
reading some of the research

00:48:43.030 --> 00:48:45.860
on what causes some people
to grow into givers.

00:48:45.860 --> 00:48:47.570
And I'll just highlight
a couple of patterns.

00:48:47.570 --> 00:48:49.570
I'm happy to share more details
if anybody wants to

00:48:49.570 --> 00:48:50.890
read the studies.

00:48:50.890 --> 00:48:53.490
One is parenting styles
are obviously huge.

00:48:53.490 --> 00:48:56.030
If you are a role model as a
parent as a giver, obviously

00:48:56.030 --> 00:48:57.890
