to follow suit.

00:48:57.890 --> 00:49:01.430
Also, there's some really cool
data showing that parents who

00:49:01.430 --> 00:49:04.360
end up basically giving their
children a lot of freedom are

00:49:04.360 --> 00:49:07.070
more likely to encourage their
children to become givers.

00:49:07.070 --> 00:49:10.050
Whereas those who restrict
freedom then essentially raise

00:49:10.050 --> 00:49:12.320
kids who want to restrict the
freedom of the other people

00:49:12.320 --> 00:49:14.680
around them, which is sort of,
I think, a little bit more of

00:49:14.680 --> 00:49:16.140
a taker move.

00:49:16.140 --> 00:49:17.470
The other really interesting
data

00:49:17.470 --> 00:49:19.820
point on this is siblings.

00:49:19.820 --> 00:49:21.430
So this is Paul van
Lange's research.

00:49:21.430 --> 00:49:24.470
What Paul shows is that a lot
of people think first borns

00:49:24.470 --> 00:49:26.840
are more likely to be givers
because you get a lot of

00:49:26.840 --> 00:49:29.050
responsibility training if you
have younger siblings.

00:49:29.050 --> 00:49:32.010
You have to share and care
and feed and babysit.

00:49:32.010 --> 00:49:35.140
And it's actually the opposite
in a weird sense, which is

00:49:35.140 --> 00:49:37.720
just don't be the last born.

00:49:37.720 --> 00:49:39.700
As long as you have at least one
younger sibling, and then

00:49:39.700 --> 00:49:42.030
the more of them you have, the
more of this responsibility

00:49:42.030 --> 00:49:44.120
training you get and the more
you tend to gravitate in the

00:49:44.120 --> 00:49:45.280
giver direction.

00:49:45.280 --> 00:49:47.320
One other sibling pattern that
I think is really interesting

00:49:47.320 --> 00:49:50.050
is van Lange shows that people
who do a lot of generous

00:49:50.050 --> 00:49:53.340
giving are twice as likely to
have sisters as brothers.

00:49:53.340 --> 00:49:56.930
And you could ask, well, back
to Tina's question, why do

00:49:56.930 --> 00:49:58.490
sisters turn us into givers?

00:49:58.490 --> 00:49:59.740
And there's a debate
about that.

00:49:59.740 --> 00:50:01.300
I don't want to speculate
too far.

00:50:01.300 --> 00:50:04.160
But two of the popular
explanations are one, women

00:50:04.160 --> 00:50:07.070
basically earlier on start
giving, and so that rubs off

00:50:07.070 --> 00:50:08.140
on their siblings.

00:50:08.140 --> 00:50:09.760
And then two, there's
some data--

00:50:09.760 --> 00:50:12.010
Jonathan Haidt argues that
girl babies are literally

00:50:12.010 --> 00:50:15.140
cuter than boy babies, and so
they attract more empathy and

00:50:15.140 --> 00:50:16.360
then people want to help them
more, and then they

00:50:16.360 --> 00:50:17.300
get into the habit.

00:50:17.300 --> 00:50:19.720
Again, this is going very
far beyond data.

